"""
MKT Christ Commentary — Numbers chapters 14–15
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-numbers-14-15-fill.py

Key decisions:
- Ch 14: Kadesh rebellion treated as the NT's paradigm case of unbelief (Heb 3-4, 1 Cor 10);
  v18 Exod 34:6-7 citation is a direct revelation of God's character, the highest classification;
  v29 is direct (Heb 3:17 quotes it explicitly); v36 tzitzit / Heb 13:12 is a type.
- Ch 15: Sacrificial laws classified as types; Gentile-inclusion verses (15-16) as shadow;
  v30 high-handed sin treated as revelation of God pointing to Heb 10:26;
  v36 (outside the camp) is a type with explicit NT citation (Heb 13:12);
  v38-41 tzitzit as type — Christ embodies Torah, his garment heals (Matt 9:20).
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

NUMBERS = {
  "14": {
    "1": '<p>A revelation of God: the congregation weeping through the night captures the depth of faithlessness that can seize even a people who have witnessed divine wonders. The NT uses the wilderness generation\'s failure precisely here — not as ancient history but as an active warning to the church (Heb 3:7-19; 1 Cor 10:1-12): the same pattern of hearing and not trusting is always possible for those who have encountered God\'s grace.</p>',
    "2": '<p>A theme: Israel\'s grumbling against Moses and Aaron rehearses the larger biblical pattern of rejecting God\'s appointed mediators. The pattern culminates in the rejection of Christ (John 1:11: he came to his own, and his own did not receive him), making the Kadesh rebellion the structural type of the ultimate rejection.</p>',
    "3": '<p>A revelation of God: the people\'s distortion of divine motive — "why is the LORD bringing us into this land to fall by the sword?" — reveals how fear rewrites providence as malice. Christ comes precisely to correct this distorted vision of the Father, presenting God as the one who gives life, not the one who leads into destruction (John 10:10).</p>',
    "4": '<p>A shadow: the desire to appoint a new leader and return to Egypt — preferring the slavery they knew to the promise they could not see — foreshadows every later turning away from God\'s promise. The NT warns against this same backward movement: "No one who puts his hand to the plow and looks back is fit for the kingdom of God" (Luke 9:62).</p>',
    "5": '<p>A type: Moses and Aaron falling facedown before the congregation is an act of intercession — placing themselves between the people\'s failure and divine judgment. This posture anticipates Christ as the great intercessor who stands between sinners and the Father\'s just response to rebellion (Heb 7:25).</p>',
    "6": '<p>A revelation of God: Joshua and Caleb tearing their clothes at the congregation\'s unbelief express the grief of the faithful at God\'s purposes being rejected. Their minority faithfulness within mass apostasy is the pattern of the remnant — and ultimately of Christ himself, faithful in the midst of a faithless generation.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A theme: "an exceedingly good land" is the content of the promise the congregation refuses to trust. The physical land points forward to a better country — the one Abraham and the patriarchs sought (Heb 11:14-16), the city whose architect and builder is God, which the church now pursues in Christ.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A revelation of God: "if the LORD is pleased with us" — divine <em>ratsah</em> (pleasure/delight) as the condition of the gift. The Incarnation is the supreme expression of divine pleasure: at the baptism and transfiguration the Father declares, "This is my beloved Son, in whom I am well pleased" (Matt 3:17; 17:5), the fullest form of the divine ratsah Caleb describes.</p>',
    "9": '<p>A revelation of God: "do not fear the people of the land, for they are bread for us; their protection is removed from them, but the LORD is with us." The logic of divine presence overcoming all enemies becomes foundational NT confidence: "If God is for us, who can be against us?" (Rom 8:31). The shadow of the enemy dissolves before the presence of YHWH.</p>',
    "10": '<p>A revelation of God: the glory of the LORD appearing at the tent of meeting to vindicate Moses, Caleb, and Joshua against the threatening congregation is the divine pattern of vindicating the faithful minority. The ultimate vindication is the resurrection — God vindicating the Son who was rejected by the crowd (Acts 2:23-24).</p>',
    "11": '<p>A revelation of God: "how long will this people despise me?" — divine grief at persistent unbelief even in the face of repeated signs. This divine pathos (the pain of love rejected) is expressed most fully in Christ\'s lament over Jerusalem: "How often would I have gathered your children together as a hen gathers her brood" (Matt 23:37).</p>',
    "12": '<p>A revelation of God: the offer to disinherit Israel and make a new nation from Moses alone reveals God\'s sovereign freedom — the ability to begin again with a single faithful man. Moses does not accept this offer, interceding instead for the people. Christ does not use his position for self-advantage but gives himself for others (Phil 2:6-8).</p>',
    "13": '<p>A type: Moses argues that destroying Israel would lead the nations to conclude that YHWH was unable to bring them in. The intercession on the basis of God\'s reputation anticipates Christ, whose atoning work is simultaneously the expression of God\'s love and the vindication of God\'s justice — "so that he might be just and the justifier of the one who has faith in Jesus" (Rom 3:26).</p>',
    "14": '<p>A revelation of God: Moses rehearses YHWH\'s mighty acts — cloud by day, fire by night, the divine presence going before the people — as the basis for appealing to God\'s faithfulness. The fullness of these acts of divine accompaniment is revealed in Christ, who is Emmanuel (God with us) and promises "I am with you always, to the end of the age" (Matt 28:20).</p>',
    "15": '<p>A theme: the danger that the nations would say "the LORD was not able to bring his people in" expresses a core biblical concern — the vindication of God\'s name before the nations. This theme reaches its climax in the cross, which simultaneously appears as divine weakness and is the power of God for salvation (1 Cor 1:18-25).</p>',
    "16": '<p>A revelation of God: "the LORD was not able" — the false inference that would follow from abandoning the people. God\'s commitment to his word means he cannot abandon what he has promised without denying himself (2 Tim 2:13). The faithfulness of God to complete what he has begun is the bedrock of NT assurance (Phil 1:6).</p>',
    "17": '<p>A revelation of God: Moses appeals to the greatness of God\'s power "as you have spoken" — the spoken promise becomes the basis of the appeal. Prayer rooted in Scripture — claiming what God has already committed himself to — is the pattern Christ teaches: "Your will be done," praying the covenant promise back to the Father (Matt 6:10).</p>',
    "18": '<p>A direct revelation: Moses cites the Exod 34:6-7 self-disclosure of God — "slow to anger and abounding in steadfast love (<em>hesed</em>), forgiving iniquity and transgression." This is the most-cited divine self-description in the OT (echoed in Neh 9:17; Ps 86:15; 103:8; Joel 2:13; Jonah 4:2), expressing God\'s character as the basis for mercy. In Christ this character finds its embodiment: John 1:14 describes the Word become flesh as "full of grace and truth" — the same pairing of <em>hesed</em> and <em>emet</em> that YHWH speaks at Sinai.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A type: Moses asks for pardon "according to the greatness of your steadfast love (<em>hesed</em>), just as you have forgiven this people from Egypt until now." Intercession on the basis of God\'s character and track record anticipates Christ\'s high-priestly prayer (John 17) and ongoing intercession (Heb 7:25), where forgiveness is grounded not in the people\'s merit but in the divine mercy that sent the Son.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A revelation of God: "I have pardoned, according to your word" — the divine pardon issued on the basis of the intercessor\'s word. This pardon costs nothing visible yet — the full cost of divine forgiveness is not visible until the cross, where God "is just and the justifier" (Rom 3:26). Every act of divine forgiveness in the OT is underwritten by the coming atonement.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A fulfillment: "all the earth shall be filled with the glory of the LORD" — the eschatological promise spoken immediately after judgment. This promise recurs in Isa 11:9, Hab 2:14, and reaches its consummation in Revelation: the new Jerusalem needs no sun because the glory of God is its light and the Lamb is its lamp (Rev 21:23). Christ is the one through whom the earth is filled with the knowledge of God\'s glory.</p>',
    "22": '<p>A theme: the ten testings of God in Egypt and the wilderness describe the pattern of persistent unbelief that hardens into final rejection. The NT catalogs this pattern as warning: "They were written down for our instruction, on whom the end of the ages has come" (1 Cor 10:11). The escalating unbelief of the exodus generation is the template for understanding what Paul calls "hardening."</p>',
    "23": '<p>A direct revelation: "none of those who despised me shall see it" — the exclusion of the unbelieving from the land. Psalm 95:11 applies this verse to the concept of divine "rest," and Hebrews 3:11 quotes it as the warning to the church: "as I swore in my wrath, they shall not enter my rest." The promised rest that the wilderness generation forfeited is the rest that Christ secures for those who trust him (Heb 4:1-11).</p>',
    "24": '<p>A shadow: "my servant Caleb has a different spirit and has followed me fully." Caleb\'s "different spirit" and wholehearted (Hebrew: <em>male</em>, full/complete) following of YHWH is the OT image of the faithful servant who stands apart from the unbelieving crowd. This anticipates the NT believer who has received the Spirit — the "different spirit" being the Holy Spirit who enables the wholehearted faithfulness that the flesh cannot sustain.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A revelation of God: the painful redirection — "turn back tomorrow and set out for the wilderness" — is not abandonment but the discipline that preserves the second generation\'s future. The forty-year delay is the form divine patience takes after judgment: not extinction but formation. The NT\'s theme of divine discipline (Heb 12:5-11) draws on this pattern.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A revelation of God: the LORD speaking to Moses and Aaron continues after judgment — divine speech is not withdrawn even when its content is hard. God does not fall silent in his displeasure; he speaks both judgment and hope. Christ is the Word who continues to speak, even from the cross.</p>',
    "27": '<p>A revelation of God: "how long shall I bear with this wicked congregation?" — divine long-suffering reaching its limit. YHWH has heard the grumbling. The divine hearing is both grace (he hears prayer) and judgment (he hears rebellion). The patience of God that "bears all things" (1 Cor 13:7) is not inexhaustible for those who persist in rejection.</p>',
    "28": '<p>A revelation of God: "as I live, declares the LORD" — the divine self-oath on which the judgment rests. God swears by himself because there is nothing greater (Heb 6:13). When God swears, the word is doubly secured. The same divine self-oath that grounds judgment also grounds the oath of the high priest\'s permanent priesthood (Heb 7:20-21).</p>',
    "29": '<p>A direct reference: "your dead bodies shall fall in this wilderness." Hebrews explicitly cites this fate — "with whom was God provoked for forty years? Was it not with those who sinned, whose bodies fell in the wilderness?" (Heb 3:17) — as the central warning against unbelief for the NT church. The wilderness corpses are the most stark biblical image of salvation begun and forfeited through faithlessness.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A type: "not one of you shall come into the land — except Caleb and Joshua." The faithful remnant entering what the mass of the unbelieving do not enter prefigures the pattern of Hebrews 4: there remains a sabbath rest for the people of God, and those who enter that rest must do so through Christ-directed faith rather than wilderness-style unbelief.</p>',
    "31": '<p>A revelation of God: "your little ones, who you said would become prey, I will bring them in." The reversal of the fearful verdict — God accomplishing for the next generation what the current generation\'s fear said was impossible — is the pattern of divine faithfulness overcoming human unbelief. The promises of God are not nullified by one generation\'s failure.</p>',
    "32": '<p>A revelation of God: the repeated death sentence — "your dead bodies shall fall in this wilderness" — is the most explicit statement of judgment in Numbers. Its repetition in Hebrews (3:17; 1 Cor 10:5) makes the wilderness deaths the paradigm case of what unbelief forfeits. The warning is meant to drive the church to the rest that Christ provides.</p>',
    "33": '<p>A theme: "forty years wandering, bearing the weight of your faithlessness." The wilderness wandering is the most sustained OT image of the cost of unbelief — an entire generation\'s life consumed. Paul identifies the wilderness events as "types for us" (1 Cor 10:6, 11), making the forty-year pattern a permanent warning for the community of faith.</p>',
    "34": '<p>A type: forty days of spying producing forty years of consequence — the exact proportionality of the sentence. "You shall bear your iniquity" (<em>tis\'u et awonotekhem</em>) uses the same verb as Isa 53:11 — "he shall bear their iniquities." Israel bears its own iniquity in the wilderness; Christ bears the iniquity of others at the cross.</p>',
    "35": '<p>A revelation of God: "I, the LORD, have spoken. Surely I will do this." The finality of the divine word is the ground of both judgment and promise. The same certainty that attaches to the judgment on the wilderness generation attaches to the promises of the new covenant: "He who promised is faithful" (Heb 10:23).</p>',
    "36": '<p>A revelation of God: the ten faithless spies die immediately by plague — swift judgment on those who led the congregation into unbelief. Their responsibility as report-bearers is enormous: they caused the whole assembly to sin. The NT emphasizes the gravity of leading God\'s people astray: "Let not many of you become teachers" (James 3:1).</p>',
    "37": '<p>A revelation of God: "those men who brought up a bad report about the land died by plague before the LORD." The specific form of their death — plague, before YHWH — links cause and effect with precision. Those who spoke faithlessly against God\'s gift receive the judgment their words invited.</p>',
    "38": '<p>A type: "only Joshua son of Nun and Caleb son of Jephunneh remained alive." Two faithful witnesses out of twelve is the remnant principle: God preserves a faithful remnant even when judgment falls on the whole. The church is the NT remnant, those who remain in Christ when the mass of Israel does not (Rom 11:5).</p>',
    "39": '<p>A revelation of God: the people mourned greatly — but the mourning comes too late, after the word of judgment is spoken. The NT uses this pattern of untimely repentance as a warning: Esau found no chance to repent "though he sought it with tears" (Heb 12:17) because he had sold his birthright before he grieved its loss. Godly sorrow must precede, not follow, the closing of the opportunity.</p>',
    "40": '<p>A revelation of God: the presumptuous attempt to enter the land the next day — "here we are; we will go up to the place the LORD has promised" — after the sentence has been pronounced reveals how sin does not undo itself by renewed effort. The self-will that refused God\'s gift cannot be corrected by self-willed obedience. Grace cannot be commandeered.</p>',
    "41": '<p>A revelation of God: "why are you transgressing the LORD\'s command? This will not succeed." Moses speaks the divine boundary with clarity: after judgment is pronounced and divine commission is withdrawn, no human initiative can substitute for divine direction. The same principle governs the church: fruitful service flows from divine calling, not self-assertion.</p>',
    "42": '<p>A revelation of God: "the LORD is not among you; lest you be struck down before your enemies." The presence of YHWH is the decisive factor in battle — not numbers, not terrain, not courage. The fullest expression of this presence is Christ as Emmanuel, whose permanent presence with his people through the Spirit (Matt 28:20; John 14:16-17) is the new covenant fulfillment of the dwelling of God.</p>',
    "43": '<p>A revelation of God: without YHWH, the same enemies described as "bread for us" (v9) become destroyers. The transformation is not in the enemies but in the divine presence. This is the logic of John 15:5 — "apart from me you can do nothing." The power for effective life and mission is entirely contingent on union with Christ.</p>',
    "44": '<p>A revelation of God: going up "even though the ark of the covenant of the LORD and Moses did not leave the camp." The ark as the symbol of divine presence and authorization: action without divine commissioning is presumption regardless of how spiritually motivated it appears. The NT equivalent is action outside of Christ\'s sending (John 20:21; Acts 13:2-3).</p>',
    "45": '<p>A revelation of God: defeated at Hormah — the name meaning "devoted to destruction." The place of their failure becomes the name that defines it. The defeat is not abandonment by God but the consequence of self-willed action outside of covenant. The church\'s effectiveness depends entirely on the authorization that comes through abiding in Christ (John 15:1-8).</p>'
  },
  "15": {
    "1": '<p>A revelation of God: divine speech continues in Numbers 15 immediately after the judgment of chapter 14 — God begins giving new instructions for when the next generation enters the land. The word of God does not fall silent in judgment; grace and instruction persist. Christ is the living Word who never ceases to speak (Heb 1:2; Rev 3:20).</p>',
    "2": '<p>A revelation of God: "when you come into the land you are to inhabit, which I am giving you" — the land-entrance is stated as certain even after the preceding judgment. God\'s promise to the second generation stands firm despite the first generation\'s failure. This is the pattern of divine faithfulness that Paul develops: the unbelief of some does not nullify the faithfulness of God (Rom 3:3).</p>',
    "3": '<p>A type: the sacrificial offerings by fire — burnt offering, vow fulfillment, freewill offering — constitute the structure of Israel\'s worship. Every offering is a shadow of the one full, final, and sufficient sacrifice of Christ, who offered himself as a "pleasing aroma" to God (Eph 5:2: "a fragrant offering and sacrifice to God").</p>',
    "4": '<p>A type: the grain offering of fine flour mixed with oil accompanying every sacrifice is the bread-component of the covenant meal shared with God. The Lord\'s Supper is the new covenant fulfillment of this meal — bread and cup shared in the presence of God as the substance of what the grain and drink offerings foreshadowed (1 Cor 11:23-26).</p>',
    "5": '<p>A type: wine as the drink of the covenant offering — a quarter hin of wine accompanying the sacrifice. Jesus at the Last Supper identifies the cup as "my blood of the covenant, which is poured out for many" (Matt 26:28), making the wine of the new covenant meal the fulfillment of every cup poured out in Israel\'s sacrificial worship.</p>',
    "6": '<p>A type: the graduated offerings — different quantities for lambs, rams, and bulls — reflect the gradations of the sacrificial system. Christ\'s single sacrifice supersedes all gradations: the "more perfect" sacrifice of Hebrews 9:11-12 fulfills the entire graduated system with one complete offering.</p>',
    "7": '<p>A type: "a pleasing aroma to the LORD" — the drink offering of wine described in terms of the sacrificial fragrance that ascends to God. Ephesians 5:2 applies this language directly to Christ: he gave himself up for us, "a fragrant offering and sacrifice to God," identifying the cross as the fulfillment of every pleasing aroma in Israel\'s worship.</p>',
    "8": '<p>A type: the young bull — the most costly animal in the sacrificial scale — accompanied by the largest grain and wine portions. Hebrews contrasts Israel\'s bull sacrifices with Christ\'s self-offering: "it is impossible for the blood of bulls and goats to take away sins" (Heb 10:4), but Christ "through his own blood entered once for all into the holy places" (Heb 9:12).</p>',
    "9": '<p>A type: three-tenths of an ephah of fine flour for the bull\'s grain offering — the largest portion in the table. The fullness of the grain offering accompanying the greatest sacrifice points to Christ\'s offering as complete and final; nothing is lacking in his self-giving (Col 2:9-10: "in him the whole fullness of deity dwells bodily").</p>',
    "10": '<p>A type: half a hin of wine for the bull\'s drink offering — the largest wine portion, a pleasing aroma. The ascending quantity of wine across the sacrifice scale (quarter hin for lamb, third hin for ram, half hin for bull) creates a table of escalating completeness that finds its terminus in Christ, who gives his blood as the one offering that establishes the new covenant (Luke 22:20).</p>',
    "11": '<p>A type: "this shall be done for each bull, each ram, and each lamb or goat" — the rule of repetition applies to every animal. The necessity of repeating the sacrificial rite for every offering reflects the inability of the OT system to achieve permanent atonement. Hebrews draws this contrast explicitly: "every priest stands daily at his service" because the work is never finished; "when Christ had offered for all time a single sacrifice for sins, he sat down" (Heb 10:11-12).</p>',
    "12": '<p>A type: "whatever the number of animals you offer, do this for each one according to their number." The multiplicability of the system — the same rule for one or a thousand animals — underscores its provisional character. No quantity of OT sacrifices achieves what one sacrifice of Christ accomplishes (Heb 9:26: "he has appeared once for all at the end of the ages to put away sin by the sacrifice of himself").</p>',
    "13": '<p>A revelation of God: "every native Israelite shall follow this procedure" — the law applies to all who belong to the covenant community. The universal scope of the law\'s requirement prepares for the universal scope of Christ\'s fulfillment: "he is the propitiation for our sins, and not for ours only but also for the whole world" (1 John 2:2).</p>',
    "14": '<p>A shadow: the resident alien (<em>ger</em>) who presents an offering following the same procedure as the native Israelite is incorporated into Israel\'s sacrificial worship. This inclusion of the stranger foreshadows the Gentile inclusion in Christ: "he has made us both one and has broken down the dividing wall of hostility" (Eph 2:14), making the stranger a full participant in the household of God.</p>',
    "15": '<p>A shadow: "there shall be one statute for the congregation — for you and for the resident alien." One law for native and stranger in the community of worship directly anticipates Paul\'s proclamation that in Christ "there is neither Jew nor Greek, neither slave nor free, neither male nor female, for you are all one in Christ Jesus" (Gal 3:28). The numerical oneness of the statute becomes the theological oneness of the body.</p>',
    "16": '<p>A shadow: "one law and one rule shall apply to you and to the resident alien." The unity of the law in the covenant community points to the one mediator of the new covenant: "there is one God, and there is one mediator between God and men, the man Christ Jesus" (1 Tim 2:5). The singularity of the rule is the singularity of the way into the Father\'s presence.</p>',
    "17": '<p>A revelation of God: divine speech to Moses continues — God teaching his people about life in the promised land before they are even there. This anticipatory instruction reveals the God who gives frameworks for flourishing before the circumstances arrive. Christ gives his disciples instructions for the mission they will carry out in his absence (Matt 28:18-20; John 14-16).</p>',
    "18": '<p>A revelation of God: "when you come into the land to which I am bringing you" — the certainty of arrival expressed as the premise for instruction. God legislates for a future he has guaranteed. The God who brings his people into rest (the land) is the same God who "has caused us to be born again to a living hope" (1 Pet 1:3) for an imperishable inheritance.</p>',
    "19": '<p>A type: the firstfruits offering from the land\'s produce — presenting the first portion to the LORD. 1 Corinthians 15:20 applies the firstfruits concept directly to Christ: "Christ has been raised from the dead, the firstfruits of those who have fallen asleep." Jesus is the first-fruits of the resurrection harvest; his resurrection guarantees the resurrection of all who belong to him.</p>',
    "20": '<p>A type: "<em>challah</em>" — the first of the dough presented as a loaf to the LORD. The firstfruits of the ground and the firstfruits of the dough both express the principle that the first belongs to God. Colossians 1:15-18 applies this principle to Christ as "the firstborn of all creation" and "the firstborn from the dead," the one in whom and through whom all things are presented back to the Father.</p>',
    "21": '<p>A type: "from the first of your dough you shall give the LORD a contribution throughout your generations." The ongoing firstfruits obligation across generations points to the permanent, once-for-all firstfruits offering of Christ\'s resurrection. What Israel repeated each generation, Christ fulfills once in a way that makes repetition unnecessary: he is the eternal firstfruits (Rev 1:5: "the firstborn of the dead").</p>',
    "22": '<p>A type: "if you sin unintentionally and do not observe all these commandments" — the category of unintentional sin (<em>shegagah</em>) requiring atonement. The sacrificial system acknowledges that even sins committed in ignorance constitute a breach of covenant and require covering. Christ\'s atoning death covers not only deliberate sins but those committed in ignorance (Luke 23:34: "Father, forgive them, for they know not what they do").</p>',
    "23": '<p>A revelation of God: "all that the LORD commanded you through Moses, from the day the LORD gave the command" — the scope of the commandment covering the entire Mosaic revelation. Christ comes not to abolish this comprehensive commandment but to fulfill it (Matt 5:17), embodying in his person the whole of what the law requires.</p>',
    "24": '<p>A type: if the community sins unintentionally without the congregation\'s knowledge, the whole congregation presents a burnt offering for the whole assembly. The principle of communal atonement for shared sin anticipates Christ\'s sacrifice as the atonement for the whole people: "he is the propitiation for our sins" — not for individual sins only but for the corporate failure of humanity.</p>',
    "25": '<p>A type: "the priest shall make atonement for the whole congregation of Israel, and they shall be forgiven." The priestly atonement achieving communal forgiveness is the OT foundation for Christ\'s high-priestly work. Hebrews 9:11-14 presents Christ as the high priest who enters the greater tabernacle and achieves by his own blood the "eternal redemption" that the Aaronic priests could only approximate.</p>',
    "26": '<p>A shadow: "the whole congregation of Israel shall be forgiven, along with the resident alien living among them, since all the people were involved unintentionally." The inclusive forgiveness — covering both native and stranger — prefigures the scope of Christ\'s atonement, which crosses every ethnic and social boundary: "he himself is the propitiation for our sins, and not for ours only but also for the whole world" (1 John 2:2).</p>',
    "27": '<p>A type: the individual who sins unintentionally brings a yearling female goat for a sin offering. The provision for individual sin alongside communal atonement reflects the double scope of Christ\'s work — his death is both for the community as a whole and for each believer individually: "the Son of God, who loved me and gave himself for me" (Gal 2:20).</p>',
    "28": '<p>A type: "the priest shall make atonement before the LORD for the person who sinned unintentionally, making atonement for that person, and he shall be forgiven." The priestly mediation achieving personal forgiveness is the OT pattern that Christ fulfills as the one mediator between God and man — the high priest who not only makes atonement but is himself the atoning sacrifice (1 John 2:1-2).</p>',
    "29": '<p>A shadow: "you shall have one law for the person who acts unintentionally, whether native-born among the Israelites or a resident alien." The unity of the law across every social boundary anticipates the oneness of the gospel: one Lord, one faith, one baptism (Eph 4:5), equally available to all who approach through Christ.</p>',
    "30": '<p>A revelation of God: "the person who acts defiantly (<em>beyad ramah</em>, with a high hand) — that person blasphemes the LORD and shall be cut off." The high-handed sin — deliberate, knowing rejection of God\'s word — is the category for which the sacrificial system provides no atonement. Hebrews 10:26-27 draws on exactly this distinction: "if we sin deliberately after receiving the knowledge of the truth, there no longer remains a sacrifice for sins, but a fearful expectation of judgment." The cross covers sins committed in weakness; persistent, knowing contempt of God\'s grace places itself outside the covenant.</p>',
    "31": '<p>A revelation of God: "that person shall be utterly cut off (<em>hikaret tikaret</em>); his guilt is on himself." The <em>karet</em> penalty — being cut off from the people — is the most severe covenant sanction short of death. Christ bears the ultimate <em>karet</em> on behalf of those who believe (Gal 3:13: "Christ redeemed us from the curse of the law by becoming a curse for us"), so that those in him need not bear their own guilt.</p>',
    "32": '<p>A revelation of God: the narrative of the Sabbath wood-gatherer is the law\'s test case immediately following the high-handed sin law. Gathering wood on the Sabbath — a deliberate, visible act — represents the kind of knowing violation that the preceding statute addressed. The Sabbath law\'s severity reveals the seriousness with which God treats covenant structure.</p>',
    "33": '<p>A revelation of God: bringing the man to Moses, Aaron, and the whole congregation for judgment reveals the communal nature of covenant keeping. The violation of one affects the whole community. Christ\'s role as the one who "takes away the sin of the world" (John 1:29) addresses the social dimension of sin — its impact on the covenant community — not merely the individual\'s guilt.</p>',
    "34": '<p>A revelation of God: "they put him in custody, because it had not been made clear what should be done to him." Even in the Mosaic system, interpretive uncertainty required pausing before applying the law. This points to the need for the one who embodies and fulfills the law\'s intent — Christ, who does not merely apply rules but is himself the living Word who gives the law its final meaning.</p>',
    "35": '<p>A revelation of God: "the man shall be put to death; the whole congregation shall stone him with stones outside the camp." The death penalty for Sabbath violation reveals the weight of the covenant commitment. Galatians 3:13 explains the cross in these terms: Christ became a curse for us — bearing the death that the law pronounced on covenant violation — so that those in him are freed from the law\'s death sentence.</p>',
    "36": '<p>A type with direct NT citation: executed "outside the camp." Hebrews 13:12 draws on this precise location: "Jesus also suffered outside the gate in order to sanctify the people through his own blood." The exclusion from the sacred camp is the form that covenant judgment takes; Christ, bearing that judgment, is himself executed outside the holy city, fulfilling the spatial logic of the law\'s most severe penalty.</p>',
    "37": '<p>A revelation of God: the LORD speaks to Moses again — divine instruction continues immediately after the judicial execution. God\'s teaching is uninterrupted by the hard acts of covenant enforcement. The one who must say "the man shall be put to death" is the same one who immediately turns to give life-giving instructions about the tzitzit. Judgment and grace flow from the same source.</p>',
    "38": '<p>A type: "make tassels (<em>tzitzit</em>) on the corners of your garments, and put a cord of blue (<em>tekhelet</em>) on each tassel." The tzitzit are a visible embodiment of Torah on the body. Jesus wears this garment — he is an observant Jew who keeps the Torah — and his <em>kraspedon</em> (hem/tassel) becomes a point of healing: the woman with the hemorrhage touches the hem of his garment and is healed (Matt 9:20; 14:36). The one who embodies the Torah\'s fullness has a garment from which healing flows.</p>',
    "39": '<p>A type: "the tassels shall be for you to look at, so that you may remember all the LORD\'s commandments and do them." The tzitzit function as a visual mnemonic for the law — an external reminder of an internal obligation. Christ is the embodiment of what the tzitzit represent: he is the living Torah (John 1:1, 14), the Word made flesh. To behold him is to behold the fullness of what God\'s instruction was always pointing toward.</p>',
    "40": '<p>A revelation of God: "so you shall remember and do all my commandments, and you shall be holy to your God." The goal of Torah-remembrance is <em>qedushah</em> — holiness, being set apart for God. The NT presents Christ as the one who achieves holiness for his people: "Christ Jesus, who became to us wisdom from God, righteousness and sanctification and redemption" (1 Cor 1:30). The holiness the tzitzit commanded, Christ provides.</p>',
    "41": '<p>A revelation of God: "I am the LORD your God, who brought you out of the land of Egypt to be your God." The Exodus-identity formula grounds every commandment in the prior act of redemption — obedience follows liberation, not the reverse. This is the structure of the gospel: "We love because he first loved us" (1 John 4:19). Baptism is the NT\'s Exodus (1 Cor 10:1-2), and life in the Spirit is the NT\'s walking in the commandments of the God who has already redeemed his people.</p>'
  }
}

